<span id="freeTextContainer3871673931729810718">Peter Mayle might even convince readers who have no interest in France and are perfectly happy with a burger or a pizza to yearn for the countryside of France and their ability to turn the most mundane of foods into a sublime meal. My husband and I listened to the book again on our recent trip up to San Francisco and were once more charmed and filled with laughter at the antics of the narrator in attempting to discover the magic relationship these people df Provence have with the food of their r</span>
  <span id="freeText3871673931729810718" style="display:none">Peter Mayle might even convince readers who have no interest in France and are perfectly happy with a burger or a pizza to yearn for the countryside of France and their ability to turn the most mundane of foods into a sublime meal. My husband and I listened to the book again on our recent trip up to San Francisco and were once more charmed and filled with laughter at the antics of the narrator in attempting to discover the magic relationship these people df Provence have with the food of their region. So while our first stop on the road was In'n Out burgers (a relic of our high school years) our stop in the city was Chez Pannise in Berkeley by which time we were really channeling Peter Mayle and French cuisine! </span>
