<div id="review_2536919046" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2536919046" />
    <a title="Jessica Marquis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4314933-jessica-marquis"><img alt="Jessica Marquis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1566285349p2/4314933.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2536919046?book_show_action=true">Oct 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessica Marquis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessica Marquis" href="/user/show/4314933-jessica-marquis">Jessica Marquis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4314933-jessica-marquis?shelf=france">france</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4314933-jessica-marquis?shelf=travel-writing">travel-writing</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2536919046" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9409119911368611752">Peter Mayle makes me feel nostalgia for something I&apos;ll never be able to experience or duplicate: France in the 1990s. Slow France. A time before cell phones and the looming presence of McDo. <br/><br/>In &quot;French Lessons,&quot; Mayle provides a quirky food and wine map of the country. He visits a famed beachside café in St. Tropez, where clothing is optional. He joins a brotherhood of frog leg tasters at an esteemed ceremony in Vittel. He attends Sunday mass in Provence, a particular occasion intended to celebr</span>
  <span id="freeText9409119911368611752" style="display:none">Peter Mayle makes me feel nostalgia for something I'll never be able to experience or duplicate: France in the 1990s. Slow France. A time before cell phones and the looming presence of McDo. <br /><br />In "French Lessons," Mayle provides a quirky food and wine map of the country. He visits a famed beachside café in St. Tropez, where clothing is optional. He joins a brotherhood of frog leg tasters at an esteemed ceremony in Vittel. He attends Sunday mass in Provence, a particular occasion intended to celebrate the black truffle. <br /><br />Mayle has a talent. He presents a lot of the loveliness found in French cuisine and culture, and in the French themselves, while avoiding the cliché, idealistic, or twee. The "I fell in love with France" memoir is a genre studded with remarkably average tales. Sentences might have been copy and pasted between first-time authors. <br /><br />Mayle is different. His writing is wryly observed and often irreverent. He knows how to find the story, complete with vivid real-life characters–who might be the man next to him in a café, instructing Mayle on the finer points of eating escargot, or the hundreds of cartoonishly-costumed runners in a themed marathon where the drink of choice is fine wine. <br /><br />Immensely enjoyable; to savor and reread. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9409119911368611752" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


