<span id="freeTextContainer10172953104609668073">I found this book bo-oring. Which was surprising to me, as I loved his first two volumes about life in Provence, France.<br/>Food festivals are ok, but Mr. Mayle acts a bit full of himself as he travels from one to another of them.<br/>I don&apos;t want to sound like I am &apos;full of myself&apos;, but for example, a person who loves garlicky butter would probably like escargot. And frog legs are similar to chicken legs, but much smaller.<br/>How can a person get excited or interested in a Catholic Mass for truffles? They a</span>
  <span id="freeText10172953104609668073" style="display:none">I found this book bo-oring. Which was surprising to me, as I loved his first two volumes about life in Provence, France.<br />Food festivals are ok, but Mr. Mayle acts a bit full of himself as he travels from one to another of them.<br />I don't want to sound like I am 'full of myself', but for example, a person who loves garlicky butter would probably like escargot. And frog legs are similar to chicken legs, but much smaller.<br />How can a person get excited or interested in a Catholic Mass for truffles? They apparently did not attend enough Catholic Masses as a child. They (Catholics) pray for everything. And pray on everything. Horses, crops, good luck, life, death, whatever. I suppose I sound cynical.<br />I was disappointed in this book, could not even finish it - though I did get 2/3 of the way through it.<br />Sorry.</span>
